@article{Rogers1999,
abstract = {Underwater sound recordings were made at the fast-ice edge using a Sony WMD6C audiocassette recorder from a Massa hydrophone and a custom preamplifier. This system had a frequency response from 40-16,500 Hz 2 3 dB. The hydrophone was placed 12 m under the fast ice, between 13.5 and 14 m below the water surface. Recordings were made between 0500 and 1000 on 29 and 30 October 1993 when whales were seen within the area. A total of 3 h of these had good signal-to-noise. The whales were highly vociferous. The most commonly heard call was a amplitude-modulated call, shown in Figure 1. The carrier frequency, the central line on the sonagram between two spectral lines or side-bands, was amplitude modulated forming a series of short, narrow band pulses emitted at a high repetition rate. These sounds have been referred to as pulsed tones (Sjare and Smith 1986). The side bands were representative of the modulation pulse rate of the call; the mean side-band frequency was 1,500 Hz (n = 20, SD = 284). Minimum and maximum frequencies ranged between 1,000 and 8,500 Hz. The mean starting, ending, and carrier frequencies were: 5,648 Hz (n = 20, SD = 894 Hz), 3,887 Hz (n = 20, SD = 1,073), and 4,632 Hz (n = 20, SD = 81), respectively. All calls had “wavering” frequency modulation (Taruski 1979) (Fig. 1A) and in some instances there was additional secondary fine-scale wavering modulation (Fig. 1B). There tended to be an overall decrease in the frequency through the call (Fig. 1A). The mean duration of the amplitude-modulated calls was 0.77 sec (n = 20, SD = 0.14). There were different pulse rates in broad-band clicks; click trains (Fig. 2A, B) and rapidly occurring clicks, called burst pulses (Fig. 2C). The mean number of pulses and duration of click trains was 25 clicks (n = 20, SD = 16) and 1.18 sec (n = 20, SD = l.06), respectively. The average repetition rate of clicks within click trains was 34 clicks per sec (n = 20, SD = 19). For burst pulses (Fig. 2C) the mean minimum and maximum frequencies were 3,135 Hz (n = 11, SD = 2,040) and 10,910 Hz (n = 11, SD = 1,061), respectively, and the mean duration was 0.53 sec (n = 11, SD = 0.21). The second most common calls were whistles. The mean starting, ending, and fundamental frequencies were 5,222 Hz (n = 24, SD = 2,197), 4,283 Hz (n = 24, SD = 1,503), and 4,869 Hz (n = 24, SD = 1,749), respectively. All whistles had wavering frequency modulation (Fig. 3) on a broad scale (Fig. 3A), on a fine scale (Fig. 3B), or on both (Fig. 3A). The mean duration of whistles was 0.65 sec (n = 24, SD = 0.28).},
